1205","1204":"1204","1287":"1287","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Newbold Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1182–":"1182–Overleden","1180–Male":"1180–Overleden","1205–1287":"1205–1287","1182–Female":"1182–Overleden","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1287":"1287","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Newbold Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1182–":"1182–Deceased","1180–Male":"1180–Deceased","1205–1287":"1205–1287","1182–Female":"1182–Deceased","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1287":"1287","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Newbold Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Noel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Pierre, Normand, Antoine, Jacques, Alphonse, Leonce, Lucien, Marcel, Damien, Emile, Francois.","French and Walloon (<b>Noël</b>); English: from the Old French personal name <i>Noël</i>, Middle English <i>Noel</i>, from Old French <i>no(u)el</i> ‘Christmas’ (from Latin <i>natalis (dies)</i> ‘birthday’), used for someone born during the Christmas period. Alternatively, a nickname for someone who had some special connection with the Christmas season, such as owing the particular feudal duty of providing a yule-log to the lord of the manor, or having given a memorable performance as the Lord of Misrule. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium. Compare   Christmas   and   Newell  .","English: sometimes a post-medieval variant of <b>Knowle</b> and   Knoll   (see   Knowles  ). The loss of /k/ before /n/ is known in everyday speech by the 17th century and may have been earlier."],"variants":[{"name":"Nowell","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Noel  ,   Knowles  , or   Newell  ."]},{"name":"Christmas","meanings":["English (southeastern): nickname from Middle English <i>Criste(s)masse</i>, <i>-messe</i> ‘Christmas Day’, also ‘the Christmas season’, perhaps for someone who was born at Christmas or one who played the part of the King of Christmas in Yuletide games. The name was also established in County Waterford, Ireland, in 1622.","Americanized form (translation into English) of French <b>Noël</b> (see   Noel  )."]},{"name":"Nadal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Miguel, Francisco, Jose, Luis, Caridad, Digna, Jaime, Juan, Juan Carlos, Manuel, Otilio.","Catalan and French (Occitan): from the personal name <i>Nadal</i>, from <i>nadal</i> ‘Christmas’ (from Latin <i>natalis</i> ‘birthday’), the name given to a child born on that day or during that time of year. Compare   Noel  ."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Philip Noel was born in 1182, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Phillibus Noell in 1204, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1182–":"1182–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1205–1287":"1205–1287","1182–Female":"1182–Surnud","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1287":"1287","1182":"1182